### Suspense

Suspense lets components wait for something (like data or code) before rendering. It displays a fallback while the content is loading.

---

### Basic Usage

```jsx
import { Suspense, lazy } from 'react';

const LazyComponent = lazy(() => import('./HeavyComponent'));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
      <LazyComponent />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

### Multiple Suspense Boundaries

```jsx
function Dashboard() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>
      <Suspense fallback={<ProfileSkeleton />}>
        <UserProfile userId={userId} />
      </Suspense>
      <Suspense fallback={<PostsSkeleton />}>
        <UserPosts userId={userId} />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Suspense with Data Fetching (React 19)

React 19 integrates Suspense with async components:

```jsx
async function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const user = await fetchUser(userId);
  return <h1>{user.name}</h1>;
}

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
      <UserProfile userId={5} />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

| Aspect | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| Purpose | Declarative loading states |
| Fallback | React node shown during loading |
| Boundaries | Can be nested at any level |
| Coordination | Loading the slowest child determines display |

> **Key Point:** Suspense enables a declarative loading pattern. Use multiple boundaries for independent sections so one slow load does not block the entire page. Combine with lazy() for code splitting.

codeExample:
import { Suspense } from 'react';

function VideoPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Video Player</h1>
      <Suspense fallback={<div className="skeleton">Loading video...</div>}>
        <VideoPlayer id="abc123" />
      </Suspense>
      <Suspense fallback={<div className="skeleton">Loading comments...</div>}>
        <Comments videoId="abc123" />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}
